&#xa0;
[normal]              [bold]              [bold]              [bold]              [bold]              [bold]    [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence from British Airways
[normal] (WRT 030)
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]British Airways welcomes the opportunity to contribute to the Transport Select Committee’s inquiry into 
[normal]Winter Resilience in Transport.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]British Airways is one of the world’s leading global premium airlines and the UK’s largest international scheduled airline, carrying approximately 37 million passengers worldwide annually, on around 830 daily flights.  The 
[normal]airline employs around 40,000 people, the vast majority of these at its sites throughout the UK, and has an annual turnover of over £9 billion.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The airline’s two main operating bases are London’s Heathrow and Gatwick airports, with a smaller base at Londo
[normal]n City airport serving New York, European and domestic destinations.  From these three, British Airways flies over 280 aircraft to 173 destinations in more than 80 countries. In addition to passengers, the airline also transports cargo – more than 785,000 
[normal]tonnes of cargo are carried around the globe each year. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]British Airways’ main operating base, Heathrow, is one of the world’s busiest international airports. Unlike other major competitor hubs in Europe, Heathrow has been operating for many year
[normal]s at full capacity throughout most of the day. It is further constrained by rigorous limits on night movements and restrictions on how the capacity of its two runways is maximised. Therefore it is vital that the impact of this operating environment is full
[normal]y understood when considering the response of airlines and airport operators to winter weather disruption. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]While British Airways will continue to do everything in its power to minimise both the incidence and the impact of weather disruption, it is important to note that responsibility must lie with the airport operators and their service partners for ensuring t
[normal]hat the airport, including runways, taxiways, aprons, service roads and public access points to and from the airport, are resilient to adverse weather conditions. Heathrow Airport Limited and Gatwick Airport Limited, together with other airport operators, 
[normal]must continue to prioritise snow preparedness and provide timely, reliable and proactive responses both prior to, and during adverse weather events. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The impact of winter weather disruption on airport and airline operations is different for each event and
[normal] is highly dependent on the nature and duration of the adverse weather conditions. Despite robust contingency planning, airlines would never be able to guarantee operating a full schedule during times of significant weather disruption. This is particularly
[normal] the case at capacity constrained airports on the British Airways network, especially Heathrow. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]It should be noted that Heathrow is not the only airport affected by winter weather disruption. In fact most UK airports, including Gatwick and London City, a
[normal]nd many in Western Europe, including Paris, Frankfurt and Amsterdam, also suffer disruption during adverse winter weather conditions. However disruption at Heathrow is usually a result of a complex set of factors, key among which is the challenge presented
[normal] by attempting to recover following any operational disruption at an airport which is operating at full capacity. At peak periods of travel demand, the capability for airlines to re-book and reaccommodate disrupted customers is more challenging and does ha
[normal]ve a more detrimental customer impact for a longer duration.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]British Airways has a significant operating presence at three of the key London Airports – Heathrow, Gatwick and London City – and any disruption will therefore have a disproportionate impact on
[normal] the airline’s operations. This is especially the case at Heathrow where British Airways is the hub carrier.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.6
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Since 2010 British Airways has committed significant resources to planning and preparing for adverse winter weather conditions and the airline has
[normal] held a company-wide review of its disruption planning process. In 2013 British Airways is investing over £18 million in improving its customers’ experience during times of disruption, and ensuring that British Airways staff can be mobilised effectively to
[normal] deal with such disruption. The investment consists of developing new tools and technologies, as well as improving our training and processes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.7
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]British Airways is committed to improving the experience for its customers during disruption and their welfare i
[normal]s extremely important to us. The airline has put in place improved resilience and contingency measures to deal with severe weather conditions through its Disruption Management Programme. British Airways is also working closely with the key airport operator
[normal]s and service par
[normal]tners to ensure that they 
[normal]are
[normal] also
[normal] suitably prepared to provide welfare support for our customers during disruption. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]How resilient are the UK’s transport networks (including road, rail and air) to adverse winter weather?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]It is vital that airport operators, airlines, surface transport providers, and government agencies co-ordinate more effectively to ensure that where transport is affected by adverse weather, the impact on passengers is minimised. For example, where airline
[normal] operations are disrupted and airlines have the opportunity to recover by extending operations late into the night, it is vital that services such as surface transport provision and immigration facilities remain operational in order to minimise the risk of
[normal] further disruption to customers. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What lessons have been learned since the severe weather experienced in the winter of 2009-10?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]3.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]British Airways cannot comment on the broader lessons learned by the wider transport sector, but the following lessons have 
[normal]informed the specific approach taken by the airline since the severe weather experienced in 2009-2010, as well as disruption experienced in subsequent winters.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.2
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]To improve communications to our customers through all available channels during disruption[bold] – t
[normal]he feedback we received from customers su
[normal]ggested that there is a
[normal] need to ensure systems that display critical operational information are set up in the most effective way, and that there is a desire for earlier notification of cancellations or delays commu
[normal]nicated through more channels. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.3
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]To offer customers choice/options when their journey has been disrupted[bold] – an improved
[normal] approach to dealing with rebooking and refunds has been implemented.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.4
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Need for Improved operational planning and delivery during periods of disruption [bold]– the effectiveness of the Heathrow Air Traffic Management Demand and Capacity Balancing group (HADACAB) - which is responsible for deciding on the percentage reduction of fli
[normal]ghts needed to deal with expected disruption - and the consistency in the Met Office weather forecasting
[normal], has
[normal] indicated that these are on-going issues and more development work needs to be done. In the past, the lack of an agreed multi-lateral schedule red
[normal]uction and the success rate of the 
[normal]Met Office to forecast the severity of weather were major contributing factors to disruption. In addition, the prolonged closure of both of the runways at Heathrow for snow sweeping has had a material impact on delivering
[normal] the operation. 
[normal](Please see 6.1 for further details regarding HADACAB).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]To review and revise our command and control processes and procedures, including training[bold] – for example
[normal],
[normal] the operational triggers that indicate the most appropriate level of command a
[normal]nd escalation needed to be revisited. As a result
[normal],
[normal] a revised Crisis Management Process has now been implemented. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Providing customer facing colleagues[bold] with[bold] enhanced training and tools[bold] – a review of British Airway’s ‘Customer Support Programme’ proposition
[normal] and communication was necessary to ensure colleagues are motivated, well briefed and intelligently deployed to assist our customers during times of disruption.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.7
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Increased regularity of process and procedure exercises –[bold] [bold]British Airways has now implemented 
[normal]more regular and cross-company exercises to improve its ability to respond in a real situation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What practical changes have been made to ensure the UK is now better equipped to deal with severe weather?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]4.1
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Heathrow Airport is British Airways’ main 
[normal]operating base and any disruption at this airport is likely to have an impact on all of its operations – because of this
[normal],
[normal] Heathrow is the main focus in this section.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.2
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The airline has undertaken a full review of its response to severe weather disruption in order to introduce improvements that will help to minimise the negative impact on its passengers. As part of this review the airline has looked at the ways other compa
[normal]nies help their customers during times of disruption and listened to feedback from both customers and colleagues. 
[normal]&#xa0;
