[normal]4.5
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]A new ‘Customer Response Team’ has been introduced to increase colleague presence in the terminals during times of significant dis
[normal]ruption, by supplementing the team with office-based colleagues. British Airways has also increased its pool of volunteers who have been fully trained to support customer contact centres.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Staff at Heathrow, Gatwick and London City airports have been 
[normal]equipped with new technology to better serve customers with information and rebooking services during times of disruption. The introduction of mobile device technology in airport terminals will result in a superior and speedier resolution for the customer 
[normal]in times of disruption. This technology will also ensure colleagues have up-to-date operational flight information, and will be empowered to answer customer queries efficiently, both during normal operations and in times of disruption
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.7
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]A review of customer
[normal] hotel booking and allocation processes has been undertaken to make it more efficient. The Hotel Provision Project has been set up in partnership with Heathrow Airport Ltd (HAL) and the British Hotel Reservation Centre (BHRC), to "share inventory" about ho
[normal]tel rooms during disruption and to identify suitable facilities around Heathrow.
